      <section name='krystal'>

         <para number='1' comment='Examine Krystal'>
         Krystal is the Galaxy's supreme gossip columnist, working for magazine Galactopoliton. She has had one eye replaced with a camera so everything she sees is recorded to be used in her ascerbic columns. A holo-pencil is stuck behind one ear. She will talk to anybody in the hope of getting some good gossip, so say hello to her.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='kiss/hug/grope krystal'>
         Krystal draws back from you. "Woah there, sweet thing," she says. "I'm not into any of that physical stuff. I'll watch somebody else doing it, specially when they didn't ought to have been, but won't get involved myself. So keep your hands, and your lips, and any other body part, to yourself if you please."
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='hello boys'>
         Krystal looks up from the tape she is editing and smiles at you. "Well, hello honeybun, aren't you the cutest little guy?" She looks delighted to see you. "What kind of gossip do you have for me, I wonder... I hope it's really juicy."
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='hello girls'>
         Krystal looks up from tape she is editing and smiles at you. "Well, hello honeybun, aren't you a gorgeous babe?" She looks delighted to see you. "What kind of gossip do you have for me, I wonder... I hope it's really juicy."
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='hello things'>
         Krystal looks up from tape she is editing and smiles at you. "Well, hello honeybun, aren't you the sweetest being?" She looks delighted to see you. "What kind of gossip do you have for me, I wonder... I hope it's really juicy."
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='krystal/who'>
         "Krystal the Muse I used to be called when I started out," she explains. "I was so good at finding out people's secrets, they thought I had some kind of psychic power." She giggles at the idea.
         </para>

         <para number='7'>
         "It was rubbish, of course, I was just very good at my job. Still am, sweet thing - after all, I have been collecting gossip for centuries."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='gossip'>
         "Gossip is the lifeblood of the Galaxy, sweetie," Krystal says. "A good rumor moves faster than light, spreading from planet to planet by means unknown to science. I merely assist in that process, refining the gossip down so that I report on the truly juicy nuggets of scandal."
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='scandal'>
         "Scandal is what people want; they crave information about those in high places getting up to things they oughtn't," explains Krystal. "If a celebrity has a dirty little secret, it's not just my job, but my duty, to ferret it out and expose it to the full glare of publicity. It's my calling. And I love it, I really do, it makes me tingle."
         </para>

         <para number='10' comment='celebrit'>
         "The public is obsessed with celebrities, sugar; always have been and always will be. The sole purpose of Galactopoliton magazine is to tell you all about celebrities. And that doesn't mean people who have achieved something important - far from it. The more useless a person in the public eye is, the more the public wants to know about them. Those who are famous for being famous get more attention than those who have a skill of some kind."
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='galactopoliton'>
         "The whole purpose of Galactopoliton is to report on the doings of celebrities. Any trivial fact will do - their favorite color, the type of tentacle sheaths they wear, where they hibernated last season. But it's my job to find out the stuff they don't want us to report. It's the flip side of being famous; if you want to use the media to further your career, you've also got to accept that they're going to dig up the dirt on you."
         </para>

         <para number='12' comment='dirt'>
         "Nobody is squeaky clean. They've all done something they're ashamed of. Of course, what kind of thing that is will depend on what they are famous for. Who cares if a rockstar gets involved in something scandalous involving sex with aliens or abusing substances? Not me, not you, not anyone. Ah, but if a Galactic Administration official does that then the public gets very moralistic, and I can make a lot of money dishing the dirt.
         </para>

         <para number='13'>
         "Some holostars can raise a ruckus all they want; they are expected to be wild and crazy, that's the image they have built, they can get away with all kinds of appalling behavior. But then there's the ones with the cleancut images, who are seen as role-models for young people. Woe betide them if they get caught with their metaphorical trousers down! With any luck, I'll be there to snap that image at the most embarassing trouser-less moment."
         </para>

         <para number='14' comment='rockstar'>
         "Take the Rolling Stones," says Krystal. "Nearly 500 years they have been touring, and they may have faces as wrinkled as a Martian's hide, but they can still party hard with the best of them.
         </para>

         <para number='15'>
         "Keith has ingested more pharmaceuticals than the entire output of Phobos, Mick gets seen having relations with beings from all over the Galaxy, and not only does the public not get outraged, they expect the Stones to behave like that because it's what aging rockers do.
         </para>

         <para number='16'>
         "On the other hand, if the members of New Droids on the Block, or Z Club 9, or any of those bands designed to appeal to youngsters, started taking drugs or cavorting with alien hotties, that would be a major scandal. That's just the kind of thing I love to find out about!"
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='politician'>
         "The people, gotta love them; they have such a high expectation of those who take public office, and GA bureaucrats take great pains to keep their peccadilloes out of the press," she explains. "Mind you, it's not as if a predilection for sex and drugs and so on actually means an official can't do his, her or its job, but the people don't like it.
         </para>

         <para number='18'>
         "It's odd, but they don't get nearly so upset when financial scandals come to light, or bribery and corruption, or even massive incompetence. But I don't concern myself with those; I'm not a newsdroid."
         </para>

         <para number='19' comment='holostar'>
         "Image is everything in the holowood," Krystal tells you. "Right at the start of a career, an aspiring holostar gets channelled in a particular direction, and whatever image they choose, or have imposed on them, that's what they are stuck with. It's almost impossible to change the image later, although a few have managed it."
         </para>

         <para number='20'>
         She flips through the recordings she is editing and then shows you a hologram of simstar Brix Chanterel, with his shirt off, his well-developed muscles rippling as he breathes in and out. "Look at this guy," she says. "Gorgeous but dumb, right? A great action hero, sexually attractive, expected to be a bit wild but not to have an opinion on anything important.
         </para>

         <para number='21'>
         "He's actually very bright - went to university and got a degree before he became a holostar. But the public doesn't want him to be; his image is of the big, strong, stupid guy. Nobody would care if he was caught sleeping with an Argolian triplet nest, but they'd be pretty disgusted if they saw a picture of him reading a book."
         </para>

         <para number='22'>
         She flips a bit more and comes up with virginal beauty Twinkle, star of moralistic holos promoting honesty and fidelity. "On the other hand, little miss perfect here - she's a cutey, isn't she? - is seen as the perfect role-model for our youth, so any hint of scandal attached to her would end her career in a heartbeat.
         </para>

         <para number='23'>
         "Sad to say, I've been searching for years, but have never found anything to report on. I cannot believe she is as innocent as her image paints her, so I guess she must have great security. I'll keep looking. One day I'll catch her out."
         </para>

         <para number='24' comment='newsdroid'>
         "Well, cupcake, newsdroids don't shy away from gossip, of course, but they do a lot better at the real important stuff, like politicians on the take or businessthings on the make. I could have gone down that route; I worked for the original Fed newspaper, Line Noise, for a while, but soon realized I preferred the celebrity scandal circuit.
         </para>

         <para number='25'>
         "Besides, at Galactopoliton, I can do what I want; I don't think Hazed lets the Fed2 Star newsdroids off the leash much."
         </para>

         <para number='26' comment='hazed'>
         "I have the greatest respect for her as the editor of the Star, but I wouldn't want to work for her," Krystal says with some fervour. "She's a stickler and if things don't go just the way she likes them, she turns vicious."
         </para>

         <para number='27'>
         She leans forward to confide in you. "There's a reason she employs droids in her office rather than flesh and blood reporters; she can get away with treating them like slaves. I hear she beats them regularly, and if one of them messes up, it gets killed and converted into some piece of office furniture.
         </para>

         <para number='28'>
         "You will note that when a newsdroid gets a byline in the Star, it doesn't last very long... whatever happed to Robby, who started writing its own stories a few years ago? And then we haven't heard anything from Dot Matrix in a good while; I wouldn't be surprised if it had come a cropper and was now a heap of scrap metal in the corner of Hazed's office.
         </para>

         <para number='29'>
         "It's only the rare organic reporters like Hally Godarkly that seem to have any shelf life at the Star, and even they have to walk carefully. So no, I won't be going to work for Hazed."
         </para>

         <para number='30' comment='star'>
         "Oh honey, the Fed2 Star's a very different publication from the one I work for - it's more general, covering all areas of news and reportage, and it comes out weekly so everything is a bit slapdash. Galactopoliton is quarterly so all the articles have been a long time in the making, and we can polish them to perfection. Not that I am looking down on the Star, of course, there is a place for trashy journalism, I am sure."
         </para>

         <para number='31' comment='moon/where'>
         "I'm on the moon because I heard a rumor that Gariux Gigorax, the Trantorian opera star, was coming here for vacation. My sources tell me that he's on the verge of divorcing his wife and taking up with a trio from Algol. Well, he does have three heads so I guess it would make sense for him to get a babe for each of them...
         </para>

         <para number='32'>
         "But so far, I've not had much luck in getting close to him. They take security very seriously on Earth's moon, and don't welcome snoops of any kind. I've already been threatened by the charming gentleman who owns this bar."
         </para>

         <para number='33' comment='mario/bar'>
         Krystal lowers her voice. "Mario is a piece of work alright. He was nothing but a two-bit hoodlum when I was a young recorder, but he made himself invaluable as an enforcer to the moon's powers that be, until he took control of the security of the whole place. Running this bar is just a convenient front for him. Right now, he's mildly ticked off with me; I don't want to do anything to get him really angry!"
         </para>

         <para number='34' comment='nomatch'>
         "I don't know anything about that, honey," Krystal says, "but if you tell me more maybe there's a story in it."
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='menella'>

         <para number='1' comment='Vocab - hello'>
         Menella smiles brightly at you. "Hello", she says, "I'm Menella." She points to her name tag, which reads 'Menella Bute Smedley IV', in a rather violent purple writing.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Vocab - job &amp; who'>
         "I'm the project manager for the Selena City Works and the resident expert on projects, schedules, charts and the like." She smiles deprecatingly.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='vocab - charts'>
         "Obviously, as a project manager I use a lot of them," she explains. "Did you know, that in pre-Ming times they used to use two dimensional gant charts? I just found that out the other day. Only two dimensions! Poor things."
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='vocab - schedule I'>
         "Schedules, my dear, are the meat and drink of a project manager! I am the queen of schedules." She gestures theatrically. "I am -the- inner system specialist on schedules, everyone consults me." She lowers her voice conspiratorially, "Even Freya herself once asked for my help when she was trying to do a schedule for Bella."
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='vocab - schedule - II'>
         She mutters something that is difficult to hear, but it sounds suspiciously like, "A losing proposition if there ever was one."
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='vocab - project I'>
         "Project management." Her eyes light up, and your heart sinks. Oh no! You've triggered off a project bore. "Well..." she says and proceeds to lecture you at length about the ins and outs of project management.
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='vocab - project II'>
         After a few minutes your attention starts to wander, and you begin watching a moonbug making its way across the wall behind Menella. It may be your imagination, but just before it slips into a crack in the wall and vanishes, it seems to give Menella a two fingered salute!
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='vocab - project III'>
         ...
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='vocab - project IV'>
         "So there you have the long and the short of it..." Menella finishes her lecture. You check your chrono and realise that she's been going on for two and a half hours. No wonder you feel hungry.
         </para>

         <para number='10' comment='vocab selena I'>
         "Selena City? It was a marvel of engineering when it was built - the very first habitat not on Earth. It was actually built on time and in budget!" She pauses for your comment and you mumble something about that being most impressive. "All in a day's work for a project manager." She waggles her index finger at you.
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='vocab selena II'>
         "I have the original project schedules - they're on some sort of plant fibre material. The plans have been handed down the generations by each project manager to his or her successor," she informs you striking what she obviously believes is a dramatic pose.
         </para>

         <para number='12' comment='vocab - sol I'>
         "I don't very often leave the inner system," she tells you, "I prefer it here because the aliens seem to mostly keep to the outer system. Not that I have anything against aliens, of course," she hastens to add.
         </para>

         <para number='13' comment='vocab - sol II'>
         "Sometimes, though, I need to consult in person with my opposite number in the outer system - she's on Titan, and I have to travel out to the system borders. I do find it a bit fraught." She shudders ostentatiously.
         </para>

         <para number='14' comment='vocab - aliens I'>
         "Well", she says, with a quick look round to make sure no one else can hear what she is saying, "I don't want to sound biased, but they're not like us you know." Her manner becomes more confidential after this astounding revelation. "I mean to say, arachnids. And what about the slimy ones leaving their trails all over the floor.
         </para>

         <para number='15' comment='vocab - aliens II'>
         "I suppose we should really feel sorry for the poor benighted creatures. I'm told that we have a responsibility to help them reach the heights of our own cultural sophistication." She strikes a noble pose. "It's the Earthman's burden, as they say."
         </para>

         <para number='16' comment='vocab - bella I'>
         "Bella actually came in here to visit me once, you know." She preens. Looking round she lowers her voice in a furtive manner. "Bella is a project manager's nightmare, she only knows three measurements of time - 'two weeks', 'before Xmas', and 'in due course'."
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='vocab - bella II'>
         Menella leans closer and her voice drops to a whisper. "It's common knowledge amongst the project manager community..." you have visions of serried ranks of project managers, stretching into the distance, "...that Bella was late with the creation of the Federation universe!
         </para>

         <para number='18' comment='vocab - bella III'>
         "The rumour is that she only got away with it because time didn't exist before the start of the universe. Mind you, there is a school of thought that says she cheated and ran time backwards to make it appear on schedule!" She taps the side of her nose. "Enough said."
         </para>

         <para number='19' comment='vocab - hazed I'>
         "Hazed? She drops in regularly to chat. Why, only the other day she offered me a chocolate from that box she carries all the time. She said I could have any of the ones with teeth marks on them, because she doesn't like hard centres. I'm sure she has a miniature teleporter in the box. When I took the chocolate, another immediately materialised in it's place!
         </para>

         <para number='20' comment='vocab - hazed II'>
         Hazed and I are like that." She entwines her fingers to show just how 'close' she and Hazed are purported to be. This was probably not a good idea on Menella's part, since she then needs your assistance to untwine them.
         </para>

         <para number='21' comment='vocab - freya'>
         "Of course I know Freya", she pouts indignantly. "She's the patron demi-goddess of project managers. Freya and I go back years, we went to the Horsell High School prom together."
         </para>

         <para number='22' comment='vocab - bye I'>
         "Goodbye", she trills, "Doooo come and see me again, it's been soooo nice chatting to you."
         </para>

         <para number='23' comment='vocab - bye II'>
         As you turn to go, her communicator chimes and she answers it. "Yes sir. At once, sir. I'm sorry about the cost overrun, sir, but you know how it is with arachnids, it's impossible to get them to use all their legs. What! You hold me responsible, but how could I know? What do you mean it's my job to know..."
         </para>

         <para number='24' comment='vocab - nomatch'>
         Menella looks at you blankly; obviously the concept is outside her experience!
         </para>

      </section>

      <section name='wrench'>

         <para number='1' comment='Get sonic wrench'>
         It is much heavier than it looks!
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Drop sonic wrench'>
         The wrench lands on your foot, and the sonic gripping operation starts to squeeze your toes (or equivalent) in a painful fashion. With a shout, you kick the wrench away across the room, where it lands with a noisy clatter.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='Roomex'>
         With a shout, %s kicks the wrench across the room - it must have landed on a foot or equivalent body part - where it lands with a loud clatter.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Wrench is returned - room msg'>
         A moment later, a small droid skitters across the room and retrieves the wrench, presumably to return it to the place it belongs.
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='Take wrench away when leaving'>
         As you step out of the workshop, a small droid skitters up and tells you that it is forbidden to remove tools from the room unless you have authorization. It demands that you return the sonic wrench, and won't let you leave until you do. You shrug and hand it over - you didn't really want it, anyway!
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='Use wrench'>
         That is not possible, for a number of reasons: 1) there is nothing here that needs to be tightened or loosened; 2) you do not know how to operate the wrench; and 3) you are not a trained and licensed operator, so using this equipment would be against the health and safety regulations.
         </para>

